{
  "VSEPR stands for:": "",
  "Very Simple Electron Pair Repulsion": "",
  "Variable Shape Electron Proton Ratio": "",
  "Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion": "",
  "Valence Suborbital Electron Pair Rotation": "",
  "VSEPR (pronounced 'vesper') theory predicts 3D molecular geometry. The core idea: electron pairs (bonding and lone) around a central atom repel each other and arrange to be as far apart as possible.": "",
  "A molecule with 4 bonding pairs and 0 lone pairs has what shape?": "",
  "Tetrahedral": "",
  "Bent": "",
  "Trigonal planar": "",
  "Linear": "",
  "Four electron pairs maximize distance by pointing to the corners of a tetrahedron, giving bond angles of 109.5°. Methane (CH₄) is the classic example.": "",
  "A molecule with 2 bonding pairs and 0 lone pairs has what shape?": "",
  "Two bonding pairs repel to opposite sides of the central atom, forming a straight line with 180° bond angle. Examples: CO₂ (O=C=O) and BeCl₂.": "",
  "A molecule with 3 bonding pairs and 1 lone pair has what shape?": "",
  "Trigonal pyramidal": "",
  "The electron geometry is tetrahedral (4 pairs total), but one position is a lone pair. The visible molecular shape is trigonal pyramidal with ~107° bond angles. NH₃ is the classic example.": "",
  "The bond angle in a tetrahedral molecule is approximately:": "",
  "120°": "",
  "180°": "",
  "109.5°": "",
  "90°": "",
  "The tetrahedral angle of 109.5° is the angle that maximizes the distance between 4 points on a sphere. It appears throughout organic chemistry — every sp³ carbon has approximately this angle.": "",
  "Lone pairs of electrons affect molecular shape by:": "",
  "Adding to the bond angle by increasing electron density between atoms": "",
  "Pushing bonding pairs closer together, compressing bond angles": "",
  "Making bonds longer by stretching the distance between bonded nuclei": "",
  "Having no effect on the molecular shape or any bond angles whatsoever": "",
  "Lone pairs occupy more space than bonding pairs (they spread out more). In water, 2 lone pairs push the H-O-H bond angle from tetrahedral 109.5° down to 104.5°.": "",
  "Water (H₂O) has what molecular shape?": "",
  "Water has 2 bonding pairs and 2 lone pairs. The electron geometry is tetrahedral, but the molecular shape (what you can see) is bent at ~104.5°. The 2 lone pairs compress the bond angle below 109.5°.": "",
  "A molecule with 3 bonding pairs and 0 lone pairs has what shape?": "",
  "Three bonding pairs arrange in a flat triangle with 120° bond angles. BF₃ is a classic trigonal planar molecule with all atoms in the same plane.": "",
  "What is the electron geometry of water?": "",
  "Tetrahedral — 4 total electron pairs surround oxygen": "",
  "Bent — 2 bonding pairs push to opposite sides of oxygen": "",
  "Trigonal planar — 3 electron pairs in a flat plane": "",
  "Linear — 2 bonds form a straight line through oxygen": "",
  "Electron geometry counts ALL electron pairs (bonding + lone). Water has 4 pairs around O (2 bonding, 2 lone), so its electron geometry is tetrahedral. The molecular shape (bent) only describes the atom positions.": "",
  "What is the bond angle in a linear molecule?": "",
  "In a linear arrangement, atoms form a straight line with maximum separation. CO₂, HCN, and BeCl₂ all have 180° bond angles.": "",
  "What is VSEPR theory?": "",
  "A method for calculating atomic mass based on isotope abundance and nuclear binding energy": "",
  "A model that predicts molecular shapes based on the principle that electron pairs repel each other and arrange to minimize repulsion": "",
  "A theory about electron speed that predicts how fast electrons orbit the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "A model for nuclear structure that describes the arrangement of protons and neutrons in shells": "",
  "VSEPR uses the simple idea that electron clouds repel each other to predict geometry. Count the electron groups (bonding + lone pairs) around the central atom, then determine the shape that maximizes their spacing.": "",
  "What is a lone pair?": "",
  "Core electrons found in the inner shells that don’t participate in bonding or molecular geometry": "",
  "A single unpaired electron that occupies an orbital by itself and creates a radical species": "",
  "Electrons shared between atoms in a covalent bond that contribute to the bonding framework": "",
  "A pair of valence electrons not shared in bonding that takes up space around the central atom": "",
  "Lone pairs are non-bonding electron pairs on the central atom. They are invisible in the molecular structure but still repel bonding pairs, distorting the shape. Oxygen in water has 2 lone pairs.": "",
  "What is the difference between electron geometry and molecular geometry?": "",
  "Molecular geometry counts all electron pairs including both bonding and lone pairs around the atom": "",
  "Electron geometry counts all electron pairs; molecular geometry only describes the positions of atoms (ignoring lone pairs)": "",
  "Electron geometry ignores lone pairs and only considers the positions of bonding electron groups": "",
  "They are the same thing — both terms describe the arrangement of atoms in a molecule identically": "",
  "For ammonia: electron geometry is tetrahedral (4 electron groups). But one position is a lone pair we can't 'see,' so molecular geometry is trigonal pyramidal. Electron geometry determines the molecular geometry.": "",
  "What is a trigonal bipyramidal shape?": "",
  "A 3D shape with 5 bonding pairs, having axial positions (180°) and equatorial positions (120°), like PCl₅": "",
  "A flat triangle with 3 bonding pairs in one plane at 120° bond angles, like BF₃": "",
  "An octahedral shape with 6 bonding pairs at 90° angles around a central atom, like SF₆": "",
  "A shape with 4 bonding pairs in a tetrahedron at 109.5° angles, like CH₄": "",
  "Trigonal bipyramidal occurs with 5 electron groups. Three equatorial positions form a triangle (120° apart), and two axial positions are above and below (90° from equatorial). PCl₅ and PF₅ are examples.": "",
  "What is an octahedral shape?": "",
  "A tetrahedral with extra pairs distorting the 109.5° bond angles to produce a bent shape": "",
  "A flat hexagon with 6 bonding pairs arranged in a plane with 60° angles between each bond": "",
  "A 3D shape with 6 bonding pairs arranged at 90° angles, like SF₆": "",
  "Any 8-sided shape with pairs at all vertices, regardless of whether lone pairs are present": "",
  "Six electron pairs point to the vertices of an octahedron — imagine a square with one atom above and one below. All bond angles are 90°. SF₆ is the classic example.": "",
  "What is a seesaw molecular shape?": "",
  "A shape from 4 bonding pairs and 1 lone pair on a trigonal bipyramidal electron geometry (e.g., SF₄)": "",
  "A shape with 6 bonding pairs in an octahedral arrangement at 90° bond angles around the center": "",
  "A synonym for linear geometry with 2 bonding pairs at 180° on opposite sides of the atom": "",
  "A perfectly flat molecule with all atoms in one plane and 120° bond angles between them": "",
  "In a trigonal bipyramidal arrangement, the lone pair occupies an equatorial position (less repulsion). The remaining 4 bonds form a seesaw shape with SF₄ as the classic example.": "",
  "What is a T-shaped molecule?": "",
  "A shape from 3 bonding pairs and 2 lone pairs on a trigonal bipyramidal electron geometry (e.g., ClF₃)": "",
  "A molecule shaped like the letter H with 4 bonding pairs and 1 lone pair on the central atom": "",
  "A tetrahedral shape with 4 bonding pairs at 109.5° angles and no lone pairs on the center": "",
  "A planar square with 4 bonding pairs at 90° and 2 lone pairs above and below the plane": "",
  "With 2 equatorial lone pairs in a trigonal bipyramidal arrangement, the 3 remaining bonding pairs form a T shape with angles less than 90°. ClF₃ and BrF₃ are examples.": "",
  "What is a square planar shape?": "",
  "A flat shape with 4 bonding pairs and 2 lone pairs from an octahedral electron geometry (e.g., XeF₄)": "",
  "A tetrahedron with 4 bonding pairs at 109.5° angles and no lone pairs on the central atom": "",
  "A molecule with 6 bonds all in the same plane forming a hexagonal arrangement at 60° angles": "",
  "A perfect cube shape with 8 bonding pairs at the corners and 90° angles between all bonds": "",
  "In octahedral geometry with 2 lone pairs, the lone pairs go in opposite positions (trans) to minimize repulsion, leaving 4 bonds in a flat square plane at 90° angles.": "",
  "Why do lone pairs repel more strongly than bonding pairs?": "",
  "Lone pairs have more electrons (3 per pair) compared to bonding pairs that only have 2 each": "",
  "Lone pairs are held closer to the central atom and spread over a larger volume, creating more repulsion": "",
  "Bonding electrons have no charge so they cannot repel other electron pairs in the molecule": "",
  "Lone pairs don’t actually repel — they only affect the color of the molecule not its shape": "",
  "Bonding pairs are stretched between two nuclei, concentrated in a narrow region. Lone pairs are attracted to only one nucleus and spread out more, occupying a larger angular space and pushing harder on neighboring pairs.": "",
  "Double and triple bonds are treated as how many electron groups in VSEPR?": "",
  "Two for double, three for triple": "",
  "One — multiple bonds count as a single electron group": "",
  "They cannot be counted": "",
  "Zero": "",
  "VSEPR counts electron 'groups' (regions of electron density), not individual pairs. A C=O double bond is one group, a C≡N triple bond is one group. This is why CO₂ has 2 groups and is linear.": "",
  "A student draws CO₂ and predicts it is bent because oxygen is electronegative. Using VSEPR, why is this wrong?": "",
  "CO₂ is actually bent because oxygen’s electronegativity pulls the bonds into a V-shape": "",
  "Carbon has lone pairs that push the O atoms below 120°, creating a trigonal pyramidal shape": "",
  "CO₂ has 2 bonding groups and 0 lone pairs on carbon — VSEPR predicts linear (180°), regardless of electronegativity": "",
  "VSEPR doesn’t apply to CO₂ because it contains double bonds between the carbon and oxygens": "",
  "VSEPR ignores electronegativity differences. Carbon in CO₂ has 2 double bonds (2 electron groups) and 0 lone pairs. Two groups repel to 180°, making CO₂ perfectly linear. The O=C=O sits in a straight line.": "",
  "A biology student needs to explain why water is a bent molecule while CO₂ is linear. Using VSEPR:": "",
  "Both should be linear because they each have exactly 2 bonded atoms and belong to the same group": "",
  "CO₂ is heavier than water so gravity pulls its atoms into a straighter arrangement than H₂O": "",
  "Water has more atoms than CO₂ so the extra atoms force the molecule into a nonlinear geometry": "",
  "Water has 2 lone pairs on oxygen that push the H atoms together; CO₂ has no lone pairs on carbon, allowing the O atoms to be 180° apart": "",
  "H₂O: 4 electron groups (2 bonding + 2 lone) → tetrahedral electron geometry → bent molecular shape (104.5°). CO₂: 2 electron groups (2 double bonds, 0 lone) → linear (180°). The presence of lone pairs changes everything.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical chemist needs to determine the shape of ammonia (NH₃) for drug design. VSEPR predicts:": "",
  "Trigonal pyramidal — 3 bonding pairs and 1 lone pair on nitrogen give this shape with ~107° bond angles": "",
  "Bent — 2 bonding pairs and 2 lone pairs on nitrogen give this shape with ~104° bond angles": "",
  "Tetrahedral — 4 bonding pairs and 0 lone pairs on nitrogen give this shape with 109.5° angles": "",
  "Trigonal planar — 3 bonding pairs in a flat plane give this shape with 120° bond angles": "",
  "N has 5 valence electrons; 3 bond to H atoms, leaving 1 lone pair. Four electron groups = tetrahedral electron geometry. But since one position is a lone pair, molecular shape is trigonal pyramidal (107°).": "",
  "A materials scientist studies SF₆ for electrical insulation. VSEPR predicts its shape as:": "",
  "Hexagonal planar — 6 bonding pairs in a flat hexagonal arrangement with 60° bond angles": "",
  "Octahedral — 6 bonding pairs with 90° bond angles, high symmetry": "",
  "Trigonal bipyramidal — 5 bonding pairs with axial (180°) and equatorial (120°) positions": "",
  "Tetrahedral — 4 bonding pairs arranged at 109.5° angles around the central sulfur atom": "",
  "Sulfur in SF₆ has 6 bonding pairs and 0 lone pairs. Six groups arrange octahedrally with all F-S-F angles at 90°. This highly symmetric, nonpolar molecule is an excellent electrical insulator.": "",
  "A student determines that XeF₂ has 3 lone pairs and 2 bonding pairs on xenon. The molecular shape is:": "",
  "Bent — the 3 lone pairs push the 2 F atoms into a V-shaped geometry with a ~104° angle": "",
  "Linear — the 3 lone pairs occupy equatorial positions in trigonal bipyramidal, leaving 2 axial bonds at 180°": "",
  "T-shaped — the 3 lone pairs go into axial positions leaving 3 bonds in equatorial spots": "",
  "Trigonal planar — the lone pairs have no effect on geometry since they are non-bonding": "",
  "XeF₂ has 5 electron groups (trigonal bipyramidal). Three lone pairs fill all equatorial positions, leaving the 2 F atoms in axial positions directly opposite each other (180°) — linear molecular shape.": "",
  "An organic chemist studies formaldehyde (CH₂O). The carbon center has 3 electron groups (2 single bonds to H, 1 double bond to O). The shape is:": "",
  "Tetrahedral with approximately 109.5° bond angles between all atoms": "",
  "Linear with 180° bond angles between hydrogen and oxygen atoms": "",
  "Bent with approximately 104.5° bond angles due to lone pair repulsion": "",
  "Trigonal planar with approximately 120° bond angles": "",
  "The C=O double bond counts as one electron group. Carbon has 3 groups total (2 C-H single + 1 C=O double) and 0 lone pairs. Three groups arrange in a flat trigonal plane at ~120°.": "",
  "A food scientist studies why SO₂ is a bent molecule used as a preservative. VSEPR explains this because:": "",
  "SO₂ is linear because sulfur has no lone pairs and both bonds repel to 180°": "",
  "Sulfur has 2 bonding groups and 1 lone pair — the lone pair pushes the O atoms below 120°, creating a bent shape": "",
  "SO₂ has no lone pairs on sulfur so all electron groups are bonding pairs at 120°": "",
  "The O atoms push each other apart to 180° due to their high electronegativity": "",
  "Sulfur in SO₂ has 3 electron groups (2 bonding + 1 lone pair) with trigonal planar electron geometry. The lone pair makes the molecular shape bent with ~119° angle.": "",
  "A student is confused why BF₃ is nonpolar despite having polar B-F bonds. Using VSEPR geometry:": "",
  "B-F bonds are nonpolar because boron and fluorine have identical electronegativities": "",
  "Fluorine is not electronegative enough to create significant bond dipole moments": "",
  "The symmetric trigonal planar shape means the 3 equal bond dipoles cancel out, giving zero net dipole moment": "",
  "BF₃ is actually polar with a strong net dipole moment pointing toward one fluorine": "",
  "BF₃'s trigonal planar geometry (120° angles) creates three equally-spaced bond dipoles. When vectors of equal magnitude are spaced 120° apart in a plane, they cancel completely. Symmetry leads to nonpolarity.": "",
  "A biochemist explains that the shape of enzyme active sites matches substrate shapes. If an enzyme expects a tetrahedral carbon, which carbon would fit: CH₃OH or CH₂O?": "",
  "CH₃OH — its carbon has 4 single bonds (4 bonding groups, 0 lone pairs), giving tetrahedral geometry": "",
  "Neither is tetrahedral — both molecules have trigonal planar geometry around their carbons": "",
  "Both are tetrahedral — the carbon in each molecule has 4 electron groups with 109.5° angles": "",
  "CH₂O — it has more bonds to oxygen giving it 4 electron groups and tetrahedral geometry": "",
  "In CH₃OH, carbon bonds to 3 H's and 1 OH — 4 single bonds = tetrahedral (109.5°). In CH₂O, carbon has 2 C-H + 1 C=O = 3 electron groups = trigonal planar (120°). Only methanol's carbon fits the tetrahedral pocket.": "",
  "A climate scientist explains that methane (CH₄) traps more heat than CO₂ per molecule. Both absorb IR light, but VSEPR shapes affect their absorption because:": "",
  "CO₂ has more atoms (3 vs 5) so it should have more vibrational modes than methane does": "",
  "CH₄'s tetrahedral shape provides more vibrational modes that absorb IR radiation than CO₂'s linear shape": "",
  "Methane doesn’t absorb IR light because its tetrahedral symmetry cancels all dipole changes": "",
  "They absorb the same amount of IR radiation per molecule since both are greenhouse gases": "",
  "A nonlinear molecule with N atoms has 3N-6 vibrational modes; a linear one has 3N-5. CH₄ (5 atoms, tetrahedral) has 9 modes. CO₂ (3 atoms, linear) has 4 modes. More IR-active modes means more heat trapped per molecule.": ""
